      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the humanitarian argument carries immense moral weight, national sovereignty is a foundational concept of modern international law and political life. Debates persist because societies must balance competing goods—the right to life versus the right to self-governance and the rule of law. Treating border security as a legitimate debate point acknowledges that a functional state requires boundaries, even if those boundaries create moral tension. The debate, therefore, is less about which side is *right* and more about how a society *manages* that necessary, difficult tension.",
      "source": "target",
